HTERM_NAME_PREF_ALT_IS_META.message: Treat Alt key as Meta key

HTERM_NAME_PREF_DESKTOP_NOTIFICATION_BEL.message: Create desktop notifications for alert bells

HTERM_NAME_PREF_EAST_ASIAN_AMBIGUOUS_AS_.message: East Asian Ambiguous use two columns

HTERM_NAME_PREF_ENABLE_BOLD_AS_BRIGHT.message: Use bright colors with bold text

HTERM_NAME_PREF_ENABLE_DEC12.message: Allow changing of text cursor blinking

HTERM_NAME_PREF_SCROLL_ON_OUTPUT.message: Scroll to bottom after new output

HTERM_NAME_PREF_SCROLL_WHEEL_MAY_SEND_AR.message: Emulate arrow keys with scroll wheel

HTERM_NAME_PREF_USE_DEFAULT_WINDOW_COPY.message: Let the browser handle text copying

HTERM_PREF_ALLOW_IMAGES_INLINE.message:
Whether to allow the remote host to display images in the terminal.

By default, we prompt until a choice is made.

HTERM_PREF_ALT_BACKSPACE_IS_META_BACKSPA.message: If set, undoes the Chrome OS Alt+Backspace->Delete remap, so that Alt+Backspace indeed is Alt+Backspace.

HTERM_PREF_ALT_GR_MODE.message:
Select an AltGr detection heuristic.

'null': Autodetect based on navigator.language:
      'en-us' => 'none', else => 'right-alt'
'none': Disable any AltGr emulation.
'ctrl-alt': Assume Ctrl+Alt means AltGr.
'left-alt': Assume left Alt means AltGr.
'right-alt': Assume right Alt means AltGr.

HTERM_PREF_ALT_IS_META.message: Whether the Alt key acts as a Meta key or as a distinct Alt key.

HTERM_PREF_ALT_SENDS_WHAT.message:
Controls how the Alt key is handled.

  escape: Send an ESC prefix.
  8-bit: Add 128 to the typed character as in xterm.
  browser-key: Wait for the keypress event and see what the browser
    says. (This won't work well on platforms where the browser
    performs a default action for some Alt sequences.)

HTERM_PREF_AUDIBLE_BELL_SOUND.message: URL of the terminal bell sound. Leave it blank for no audible bell.

HTERM_PREF_BACKGROUND_COLOR.message: The background color for text with no other color attributes.

HTERM_PREF_BACKGROUND_IMAGE.message:
CSS value of the background image. Leave it blank for no image.

For example:
  url(https://goo.gl/anedTK)
  linear-gradient(top bottom, blue, red)

HTERM_PREF_BACKGROUND_POSITION.message:
CSS value of the background image position.

For example:
  10% 10%
  center

HTERM_PREF_BACKGROUND_SIZE.message: CSS value of the background image size.

HTERM_PREF_BACKSPACE_SENDS_BACKSPACE.message: If true, the Backspace key will send BS ('\x08', aka ^H). Otherwise the Backspace key will send '\x7f'.

HTERM_PREF_CLEAR_SELECTION_AFTER_COPY.message: Whether to clear the selection after copying.

HTERM_PREF_CLOSE_ON_EXIT.message: Whether to close the window when the command finishes executing.

HTERM_PREF_COLOR_PALETTE_OVERRIDES.message:
Override colors in the default palette.

This can be specified as an array or an object. If specified as an object it is assumed to be a sparse array, where each property is a numeric index into the color palette.

Values can be specified as almost any CSS color value. This includes #RGB, #RRGGBB, rgb(...), rgba(...), and any color names that are also part of the standard X11 rgb.txt file.

You can use 'null' to specify that the default value should be not be changed. This is useful for skipping a small number of indices when the value is specified as an array.

For example, these both set color index 1 to blue:
  {1: "#0000ff"}
  [null, "#0000ff"]

HTERM_PREF_COPY_ON_SELECT.message: Automatically copy mouse selection to the clipboard.

HTERM_PREF_CTRL_C_COPY.message:
Ctrl+C copies if true, send ^C to host if false.
Ctrl+Shift+C sends ^C to host if true, copies if false.

HTERM_PREF_CTRL_PLUS_MINUS_ZERO_ZOOM.message:
If true, Ctrl+Plus/Minus/Zero controls zoom.
If false, Ctrl+Shift+Plus/Minus/Zero controls zoom, Ctrl+Minus sends ^_, Ctrl+Plus/Zero do nothing.

HTERM_PREF_CTRL_V_PASTE.message:
Ctrl+V pastes if true, send ^V to host if false.
Ctrl+Shift+V sends ^V to host if true, pastes if false.

HTERM_PREF_CURSOR_BLINK.message: Whether the text cursor blinks by default. This can be toggled at runtime via terminal escape sequences.

HTERM_PREF_CURSOR_BLINK_CYCLE.message:
The text cursor blink rate in milliseconds.

A two element array, the first of which is how long the text cursor should be on, second is how long it should be off.

HTERM_PREF_CURSOR_COLOR.message: The color of the visible text cursor.

HTERM_PREF_CURSOR_SHAPE.message: The shape of the visible text cursor. This can be changed at runtime via terminal escape sequences.

HTERM_PREF_DESKTOP_NOTIFICATION_BELL.message:
If true, terminal bells in the background will create a Web Notification. https://www.w3.org/TR/notifications/

Displaying notifications requires permission from the user. When this option is set to true, hterm will attempt to ask the user for permission if necessary. Browsers might not show this permission request if it was not triggered by a user action.

Chrome extensions with the "notifications" permission have permission to display notifications.

HTERM_PREF_EAST_ASIAN_AMBIGUOUS_AS_TWO_C.message: Whether East Asian Ambiguous characters have two column width.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_8_BIT_CONTROL.message:
True to enable 8-bit control characters, false to ignore them.

We'll respect the two-byte versions of these control characters regardless of this setting.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_BLINK.message: If true, respect the blink attribute. False to ignore it.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_BOLD.message: If true, use bold weight font for text with the bold/bright attribute. False to use the normal weight font. Null to autodetect.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_BOLD_AS_BRIGHT.message: If true, use bright colors (8-15 on a 16 color palette) for any text with the bold attribute. False otherwise.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_CLIPBOARD_NOTICE.message: Whether to show a message in the terminal when the host writes to the clipboard.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_CLIPBOARD_WRITE.message:
Allow the remote host to write directly to the local system clipboard.
Read access is never granted regardless of this setting.

This is used to control access to features like OSC-52.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_CSI_J_3.message:
Whether the Erase Saved Lines function (mode 3) of the Erase Display command (CSI-J) may clear the terminal scrollback buffer.

Enabling this by default is safe.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_DEC12.message: Respect the host's attempt to change the text cursor blink status using DEC Private Mode 12.

HTERM_PREF_ENABLE_RESIZE_STATUS.message: Whether to show terminal dimensions when the terminal changes size.

HTERM_PREF_ENVIRONMENT.message: The initial set of environment variables, as an object.

HTERM_PREF_FIND_RESULT_COLOR.message: The background color to highlight find results.

HTERM_PREF_FIND_RESULT_SELECTED_COLOR.message: The background color to highlight the selected find result.

HTERM_PREF_FONT_FAMILY.message: Default font family for the terminal text.

HTERM_PREF_FONT_SIZE.message: The default font size in pixels.

HTERM_PREF_FOREGROUND_COLOR.message: The foreground color for text with no other color attributes.

HTERM_PREF_HIDE_MOUSE_WHILE_TYPING.message:
Whether to automatically hide the mouse cursor when typing. By default, autodetect whether the platform/OS handles this.

Note: Your operating system might override this setting and thus you might not be able to always disable it.

HTERM_PREF_HOME_KEYS_SCROLL.message: If true, Home/End controls the terminal scrollbar and Shift+Home/Shift+End are sent to the remote host. If false, then Home/End are sent to the remote host and Shift+Home/Shift+End scrolls.

HTERM_PREF_KEYBINDINGS.message:
A map of key sequence to key actions. Key sequences include zero or more modifier keys followed by a key code. Key codes can be decimal or hexadecimal numbers, or a key identifier. Key actions can be specified as a string to send to the host, or an action identifier. For a full explanation of the format, see https://goo.gl/LWRndr.

Sample keybindings:
{
  "Ctrl+Alt+K": "clearTerminal",
  "Ctrl+Shift+L": "PASS",
  "Ctrl+H": "'Hello World'"
}

HTERM_PREF_KEYBINDINGS_OS_DEFAULTS.message: Whether common OS keyboard bindings should be respected instead of always capturing for hterm's own use.

HTERM_PREF_MEDIA_KEYS_ARE_FKEYS.message: If true, convert media keys to their Fkey equivalent. If false, let the browser handle the keys.

HTERM_PREF_META_SENDS_ESCAPE.message:
Send an ESC prefix when pressing a key while holding the Meta key.

For example, when enabled, pressing Meta+K will send ^[k as if you typed Escape then k. When disabled, only k will be sent.

HTERM_PREF_MOUSE_PASTE_BUTTON.message:
The mouse button to use for pasting.

For autodetect, we'll use the middle mouse button for non-X11 platforms (including Chrome OS). On X11, we'll use the right mouse button (since the window manager should handle pasting via the middle mouse button).

0 == left (primary) button.
1 == middle (auxiliary) button.
2 == right (secondary) button.

This option is independent of the setting for right-click paste.

Note: The primary & secondary buttons are handled for you with left & right handed mice.

HTERM_PREF_MOUSE_RIGHT_CLICK_PASTE.message:
Paste on right mouse button clicks.

This option is independent of the "mouse-paste-button" setting.

Note: The primary & secondary buttons are handled for you with left & right handed mice.

HTERM_PREF_PAGE_KEYS_SCROLL.message: If true, Page Up/Page Down controls the terminal scrollbar and Shift+Page Up/Shift+Page Down are sent to the remote host. If false, then Page Up/Page Down are sent to the remote host and Shift+Page Up/Shift+Page Down scrolls.

HTERM_PREF_PASS_ALT_NUMBER.message:
Whether Alt+1..9 is passed to the browser.

This is handy when running hterm in a browser tab, so that you don't lose Chrome's "switch to tab/app" keyboard shortcuts. When not running in a tab it's better to send these keys to the host so they can be used in vim or emacs.

If true, Alt+1..9 will be handled by the browser. If false, Alt+1..9 will be sent to the host. If null, autodetect based on browser platform and window type.

HTERM_PREF_PASS_CTRL_N.message:
Whether Ctrl+N is passed to the browser.

If true, Ctrl+N will be handled by the browser as the "new window" keyboard shortcut. If false, Ctrl+N will be sent to the host.

HTERM_PREF_PASS_CTRL_NUMBER.message:
Whether Ctrl+1..9 is passed to the browser.

This is handy when running hterm in a browser tab, so that you don't lose Chrome's "switch to tab" keyboard shortcuts. When not running in a tab it's better to send these keys to the host so they can be used in vim or emacs.

If true, Ctrl+1..9 will be handled by the browser. If false, Ctrl+1..9 will be sent to the host. If null, autodetect based on browser platform and window type.

HTERM_PREF_PASS_CTRL_T.message:
Whether Ctrl+T is passed to the browser.

If true, Ctrl+T will be handled by the browser as the "new tab" keyboard shortcut. If false, Ctrl+T will be sent to the host.

HTERM_PREF_PASS_CTRL_TAB.message:
Whether Ctrl+Tab and Ctrl+Shift+Tab are passed to the browser.

If true, Ctrl+Tab and Ctrl+Shift+Tab will be handled by the browser as the "next/previous tab" keyboard shortcut. If false, the Tab key is sent to the host without Ctrl or Shift.

HTERM_PREF_PASS_CTRL_W.message:
Whether Ctrl+W is passed to the browser.

If true, Ctrl+W will be handled by the browser as the "close tab" keyboard shortcut. If false, Ctrl+W will be sent to the host.

HTERM_PREF_PASS_META_NUMBER.message:
Whether Meta+1..9 is passed to the browser.

This is handy when running hterm in a browser tab, so that you don't lose Chrome's "switch to tab" keyboard shortcuts. When not running in a tab it's better to send these keys to the host so they can be used in vim or emacs.

If true, Meta+1..9 will be handled by the browser. If false, Meta+1..9 will be sent to the host. If null, autodetect based on browser platform and window type.

HTERM_PREF_PASS_META_V.message:
Whether Meta+V gets passed to the browser.

On some systems, this is used to paste content.

HTERM_PREF_PASTE_ON_DROP.message:
If true, Drag and dropped text will paste into terminal.
If false, dropped text will be ignored.

HTERM_PREF_RECEIVE_ENCODING.message:
Set the expected encoding for data received from the host.
If the encodings do not match, visual bugs are likely to be observed.

Valid values are 'utf-8' and 'raw'.

HTERM_PREF_SCREEN_BORDER_COLOR.message:
The color for the border around the terminal screen.

This controls the color of the border around the terminal screen to create a visible line at the edges of the screen.

HTERM_PREF_SCREEN_BORDER_SIZE.message:
The border size in pixels around the terminal screen.

This controls the size of the border around the terminal screen to create a visible line at the edges of the screen.

HTERM_PREF_SCREEN_PADDING_SIZE.message:
The padding size in pixels around the border of the terminal screen.

This controls the size of the border around the terminal screen so the user can add some visible padding to the edges of the screen.

HTERM_PREF_SCROLL_ON_KEYSTROKE.message: Whether to scroll to the bottom on any keystroke.

HTERM_PREF_SCROLL_ON_OUTPUT.message: Whether to scroll to the bottom on terminal output.

HTERM_PREF_SCROLL_WHEEL_MAY_SEND_ARROW_K.message:
When using the alternative screen buffer, and DECCKM (Application Cursor Keys) is active, mouse scroll wheel events will emulate arrow keys.

It can be temporarily disabled by holding the Shift key.

This frequently comes up when using pagers (less) or reading man pages or text editors (vi/nano) or using screen/tmux.

HTERM_PREF_SCROLL_WHEEL_MOVE_MULTIPLIER.message:
The multiplier for mouse scroll wheel events when measured in pixels.

Alters how fast the page scrolls.

HTERM_PREF_SHIFT_INSERT_PASTE.message: Whether Shift+Insert is used for pasting or is sent to the remote host.

HTERM_PREF_TERMINAL_ENCODING.message:
The default terminal encoding (DOCS).

ISO-2022 enables character map translations (like graphics maps).
UTF-8 disables support for those.

The locked variant means the encoding cannot be changed at runtime via terminal escape sequences.

You should stick with UTF-8 unless you notice broken rendering with legacy applications.

HTERM_PREF_USER_CSS.message: URL of user stylesheet to include in the terminal document.

HTERM_PREF_USER_CSS_TEXT.message: Custom CSS text for styling the terminal.

HTERM_PREF_USE_DEFAULT_WINDOW_COPY.message:
Whether to use the default browser/OS's copy behavior.

Allow the browser/OS to handle the copy event directly which might improve compatibility with some systems (where copying doesn't work at all), but makes the text selection less robust.

For example, long lines that were automatically line wrapped will be copied with the newlines still in them.

HTERM_PREF_WORD_BREAK_MATCH_LEFT.message:
Regular expression to halt matching to the left (start) of a selection.

Normally this is a character class to reject specific characters.
We allow "~" and "." by default as paths frequently start with those.

HTERM_PREF_WORD_BREAK_MATCH_MIDDLE.message:
Regular expression to match all the characters in the middle.

Normally this is a character class to reject specific characters.

Used to expand the selection surrounding the starting point.

HTERM_PREF_WORD_BREAK_MATCH_RIGHT.message:
Regular expression to halt matching to the right (end) of a selection.

Normally this is a character class to reject specific characters.

A prompt will be displayed by the browser for each protocol, so please confirm/accept each one as it is shown. If no prompts are shown, then please see the next section for troubleshooting tips.

PROTOCOL_REGISTER_EXPLAIN_SETTINGS.message: If we've already registered handlers, or previous registration attempts were denied, then no further prompts will be displayed. Please open the dialog below, then check the registered handler settings in the ssh/sftp/etc... sections. If this program is blocked, you can delete those settings which will allow you to retry registration. If this program is already registered, but it isn't set as the default handler, you can change the default handler too.
